const e={"SR-1":{title:"Policy and Procedures",body:"[ORG] has developed, documented, and disseminated a Supply Chain Risk Management Policy consistent with NIST SP 800-161 and DoD supply chain risk management directives. Addresses purpose, scope, roles, responsibilities, and compliance. Reviewed annually. The [ISSM] is responsible for the supply chain risk management program.",tools:[]},"SR-2":{title:"Supply Chain Risk Management Plan",body:"[ORG] maintains a SCRM Plan for [SYSTEM] per NIST SP 800-161 identifying: critical system components, primary and backup suppliers, supply chain risks, and risk mitigation strategies. Critical components assessed for supply chain risk before procurement. Software verified for integrity before deployment. Reviewed annually and maintained in [TOOL:emass]. The [ISSM] and [AO] have reviewed and accepted residual supply chain risk.",tools:["emass","acas"]},"SR-2(1)":{title:"SCRM Plan | Establish SCRM Team",body:"[ORG] establishes a supply chain risk management team for [SYSTEM] with defined roles and responsibilities. The SCRM team includes: [ISSM] (team lead), [ISSO], contracting officer, and system owner. The SCRM team meets quarterly to review supply chain risk posture. SCRM team decisions are documented and reported to the [AO] annually. Team members receive supply chain risk management training.",tools:[]},"SR-3":{title:"Supply Chain Controls and Processes",body:"[ORG] establishes a process for identifying and addressing weaknesses in the supply chain for [SYSTEM]. Controls include: vendor vetting, hardware authenticity verification, software integrity checking, and tamper-evident packaging requirements. [TOOL:acas] scans new hardware before production deployment to identify known vulnerabilities. Software provenance is verified via digital signatures before installation. Supply chain incidents are reported to [ISSO] and [ISSM]. Supplier security assessments are conducted for critical suppliers.",tools:["acas"]},"SR-3(1)":{title:"Supply Chain Controls | Diverse Supply Base",body:"[ORG] employs a diverse set of approved suppliers for [SYSTEM] critical components to reduce supply chain risk. Critical security components ([TOOL:crowdstrike], [TOOL:paloalto], [TOOL:ivanti], [TOOL:acas]) are procured from different suppliers to prevent single points of supply chain failure. Supplier diversity requirements are documented in the SCRM Plan. The SCRM team reviews supplier diversity annually.",tools:["crowdstrike","paloalto","ivanti","acas"]},"SR-3(2)":{title:"Supply Chain Controls | Limitation of Harm",body:"[ORG] employs procurement strategies and acquisition processes that limit the harm from potential adversarial actions affecting [SYSTEM]. Procurement strategies include: preferred use of DISA APL-listed products, use of trusted suppliers with established security track records, and contractual requirements for supply chain security. The [ISSM] reviews supply chain harm limitation strategies annually.",tools:[]},"SR-4":{title:"Provenance",body:"[ORG] documents the provenance of [SYSTEM] components and services. Component provenance includes: manufacturer, country of origin, component history, and chain of custody. [TOOL:acas] scans identify components with known provenance issues (e.g., components from restricted countries). Software provenance is documented including: source code origin, build environment, and signing certificate. Provenance documentation is maintained in [ORG]'s CM repository.",tools:["acas"]},"SR-5":{title:"Acquisition Strategies, Tools, and Methods",body:"[ORG] employs acquisition strategies to reduce supply chain risks for [SYSTEM]. Strategies include: use of DISA APL-listed products, preference for US-manufactured components, avoidance of counterfeit components, and use of trusted suppliers. [TOOL:crowdstrike], [TOOL:hbss], [TOOL:acas], [TOOL:tenablesc], [TOOL:paloalto], and [TOOL:ivanti] are procured through authorized channels with verified supply chains. Acquisition decisions consider supply chain risk ratings.",tools:["crowdstrike","hbss","acas","tenablesc","paloalto","ivanti"]},"SR-6":{title:"Supplier Assessments and Reviews",body:"[ORG] assesses and reviews supply chain risks associated with suppliers for [SYSTEM]. Supplier assessments review: financial stability, security posture (SOC 2, FedRAMP, DISA APL), incident history, and country of origin. Critical suppliers ([TOOL:crowdstrike], [TOOL:paloalto], [TOOL:ivanti]) are assessed annually. Assessment results inform procurement decisions and contract requirements. The [ISSM] maintains supplier risk ratings and reports to [AO] annually.",tools:["crowdstrike","paloalto","ivanti"]},"SR-6(1)":{title:"Supplier Assessments and Reviews | Testing and Analysis",body:"[ORG] employs analysis and testing of [SYSTEM] components from suppliers to verify the integrity of supply chain deliverables. [TOOL:acas] scans test new components for known vulnerabilities before deployment. Software is analyzed for malicious code before installation. Hardware components are inspected for tampering. Test results are documented and reviewed by the [ISSO] before components enter production.",tools:["acas"]},"SR-7":{title:"Supply Chain Operations Security",body:"[ORG] employs OPSEC practices to protect supply chain-related information for [SYSTEM]. Supply chain details (component names, quantities, delivery schedules, supplier relationships) are treated as sensitive information. [SYSTEM] component acquisition information is shared on a need-to-know basis. The [ISSM] coordinates SCRM OPSEC requirements with [ORG]'s security officer. SCRM OPSEC practices are reviewed annually.",tools:[]},"SR-8":{title:"Notification Agreements",body:"[ORG] establishes notification agreements with suppliers regarding: security vulnerabilities, data breaches, supply chain incidents, and product changes. Notification requirements are included in contracts for critical suppliers. Suppliers are required to notify [ORG] within 24 hours of confirmed security incidents. [TOOL:crowdstrike], [TOOL:paloalto], [TOOL:ivanti], and [TOOL:acas]/[TOOL:tenablesc] vendor notification agreements are current. [ISSO] receives and acts on supplier notifications.",tools:["crowdstrike","paloalto","ivanti","acas","tenablesc"]},"SR-9":{title:"Tamper Resistance and Detection",body:"[ORG] implements tamper protection for [SYSTEM] components. Hardware components use tamper-evident seals on critical equipment. [TOOL:crowdstrike] detects unauthorized modifications to system binaries and firmware. [TOOL:hbss] provides file integrity monitoring. Secure Boot on [TOOL:win11] and server systems prevents unauthorized firmware modification. Physical inspection for tampering is conducted during quarterly physical security inspections. Tamper detection events are reported to [ISSO] immediately.",tools:["crowdstrike","hbss","win11"]},"SR-9(1)":{title:"Tamper Resistance and Detection | Multiple Stages of System Development",body:"[ORG] employs anti-tamper technologies and techniques during multiple stages of system development for [SYSTEM]. Tamper resistance is addressed at: design (hardware security features), development (code signing), manufacturing (supply chain controls), and operational stages (runtime integrity monitoring via [TOOL:crowdstrike]). Anti-tamper requirements are included in development contracts. The [ISSO] verifies anti-tamper measures during security assessments.",tools:["crowdstrike"]},"SR-10":{title:"Inspection of Systems or Components",body:"[ORG] inspects [SYSTEM] components at receipt to detect tampering and verify authenticity. Receiving inspection procedures include: physical inspection for tamper evidence, serial number verification against purchase orders, and [TOOL:acas] vulnerability scanning before deployment. Critical components are compared against vendor specifications. Inspection records are maintained for 3 years. Suspicious components are quarantined and reported to [ISSM] and supply chain risk management team.",tools:["acas"]},"SR-11":{title:"Component Authenticity",body:"[ORG] employs measures to detect and prevent counterfeit components in [SYSTEM]. Procurement is through authorized channels only. Components are sourced from original equipment manufacturers or authorized distributors. Hardware authenticity is verified via serial number verification with vendors. Software authenticity is verified via digital signatures before installation. [TOOL:acas] scans detect software with integrity violations. Suspected counterfeit components are reported to [ISSM], contracting officer, and DoD supply chain risk management authority.",tools:["acas"]},"SR-11(1)":{title:"Component Authenticity | Anti-Counterfeit Training",body:"[ORG] trains personnel in how to detect counterfeit system components for [SYSTEM]. Anti-counterfeit training is provided to: receiving personnel, system administrators, and the [ISSO]. Training covers: visual inspection techniques, serial number verification, anti-counterfeit packaging indicators, and reporting procedures. Anti-counterfeit training is provided annually and incorporated into new employee onboarding.",tools:[]},"SR-11(2)":{title:"Component Authenticity | Configuration Control for Component Service and Repair",body:"[ORG] maintains configuration control over [SYSTEM] components awaiting service or repair. Components awaiting service are tracked in [ORG]'s CM system. Components are physically controlled and access is restricted during the service period. Service providers are required to use authorized replacement parts. [TOOL:acas] scans components after service to verify no unauthorized changes were introduced.",tools:["acas"]},"SR-12":{title:"Component Disposal",body:"[ORG] disposes of [SYSTEM] components using policies and procedures protecting against exposure of sensitive information. Hardware containing CUI is sanitized per NIST SP 800-88 before disposal (MP-6). Storage media is degaussed or physically destroyed. Equipment disposal is documented with sanitization certificates. [TOOL:hbss] is uninstalled and licenses are released before disposal. Disposal records maintained for 3 years. [ISSO] approves all [SYSTEM] component disposals.",tools:["hbss"]}};export{e as default};
